\f1 \uc0\u9642 
\f0 	}TRAITS AND ECOLOGY\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1440\fi-1440\ql\qnatural\pardirnatural
\ls1\ilvl1\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}The work I want to present to you grew out of an interest in the link between species traits and community structure.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}This is the spiny water flea, Bythotrephes longimanus, which is a crustaceous zooplankton that has invaded NA lakes.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Its originally from Europe and made its way to NA in the ballast water of ships.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}One of the reasons for its successful invasion is its large spiny 'tail' that functions to keep it less palatable to fish.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Here we have the richness of cladoceran zooplankton species through time in Harp Lake, Ontario, Canada.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}The arrow here is when Bythotrephes was first detected, and was probably present some years before but below detection limits.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Clearly there has been a change in community structure as a result of the Bythotrephes invasion, and this change was most likely caused by its large spiny tail that gives it an advantage over the other zooplankton.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}This is a striking example of the influence of a functional trait on community structure.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}But arguably all patterns in community structure are causally related to the functional traits of the species involved, as purely neutral communities are presumably rare in nature.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li720\fi-720\ql\qnatural\pardirnatural
\ls1\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	
\f1 \uc0\u9642 
\f0 	}STATISTICAL ISSUES\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1440\fi-1440\ql\qnatural\pardirnatural
\ls1\ilvl1\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}This interest in traits has triggered a statistical issue in community ecology.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Virtually all empirical community ecology produces sites-by-species data tables like this, and the goal is to understand variation in community composition among sites.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}A classical approach is to characterize the sites by environmental variables, like this one, and then analyze the relationship between the community data and the environmental data.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Here we not only characterize the sites with environmental variables but also characterize the species with functional traits, like this.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}So now we have three sets of measured observed data: the trait data, the community data and the environment data.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}But there is this fourth corner down here.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Data 'holes' like this have actually created interesting methodological problems, called fourth-corner problems, that have led to the development of a variety of new statistical methods for analyzing such problems.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Here are some examples.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Why have data holes created such interest among methodologists?\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}The mind-bending thing about the fourth-corner problem is that its difficult to conceive of how to get such data into this standard form, where we have a replicates by variables data table.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Most standard analyses want our data in this form but its hard to see how this is possible with fourth-corner problems:  that is, we have an inherently multiple-table problem.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}And...it can get much worse...here's an example from an interesting experiment that actually manipulated the depth of the thermocline in a Qu\'e9bec lake.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}The fourth-corner methods don't handle data like this.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}And so my thesis is that the crux of these multiple-table problems is a challenge in data management, and not in a lack of statistical methods.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}In particular, an understanding of data management will equip ecologists with the tools to analyze multiple table data sets, much like they would analyze more standard single table problems.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li720\fi-720\ql\qnatural\pardirnatural
\ls1\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	
\f1 \uc0\u9642 
\f0 	}THE DATA MANAGEMENT-ANALYSIS INTERFACE\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1440\fi-1440\ql\qnatural\pardirnatural
\ls1\ilvl1\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}In particular, I think that the heart of the problem occurs at the interface between data management and analysis.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}The topic of data management may at first appear less exciting then data analysis  or methods development.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}But innovations in data management have been at the forefront of scientific advances for a long time.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}For example, consider this problem in linear algebra.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Those of us who remember elementary school algebra could solve this rather tediously through a series of substitutions and elementary operations.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}But we have a theory of data management, called matrix algebra, that lets us understand the solution to this problem in much simpler terms.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}By organizing these numbers into vectors and matrices, we can reformulate the problem like this.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}And a series of matrix manipulations leads us to a representation of the answer that we could enter into MATLAB or R for numerical evaluation.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}These ideas allow scientists to theorize at a higher-level of abstraction, freeing them from details.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Still, it is not that higher-level objects such as matrices are more important than their lower-level constituents, but rather that they allow us to separate higher-level from lower-level thinking.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Such a separation is at the heart of the success of the R language for statistical analysis.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}R stores data in what are called data frames, which are data tables with rows representing replicates and columns representing different variables -- here density of some species, temperature, and precipitation.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}When your data are in this form, data analysis can take place at a very high level of abstraction.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}In particular, R provides an algebra for specifying hypothesized relationships between variables -- so this says that density is related to both temperature and precipitation.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Note that this is the level that we want to think at, as ecologists.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}This is the really interesting stuff -- i.e. what is related to what?\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}And the R paradigm of data management allows us to think at this level.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}We combine data frames and formulae by passing them to model-fitting and plotting functions.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}And this creates analyses.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}This system separates data management...  (READ SLIDE)\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}(READ NEXT SLIDE)\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}So here's the standard R framework...and what we've done is to create a new kind of object called a data list, which can be used to store multiple tables.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}We allow data lists to be coerced to data frames and subsequently can be used within a standard R workflow.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li720\fi-720\ql\qnatural\pardirnatural
\ls1\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	
\f1 \uc0\u9642 
\f0 	}But R doesn't do multiple tables 'out-of-the-box'\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1440\fi-1440\ql\qnatural\pardirnatural
\ls1\ilvl1\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}OK so first some theory about this idea.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}So how do we convert multiple tables into a single one?\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}So here's the standard fourth-corner set-up with a sites by taxa abundance matrix, a sites by environment matrix and a traits by taxa matrix...and then that characteristic hole.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}With practically no exceptions, converting this to a single table will result in either lost information or redundant information...ask me after what I mean by 'practically no exceptions'.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}The simplest example of the first kind is to simply drop some data, so here I've dropped the trait data so that the two remaining matrices can be put together into a single table.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Note that this works because both tables share a dimension (i.e. the site dimension).\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}We could also summarize data, so here we multiply the abundance matrix by the trait matrix, resulting in a sites by traits matrix.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}This matrix is sometimes called a community weighted trait matrix and it can be combined with the environment matrix into a single table, again because they share the site dimension.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Although these methods have been very useful, they obviously suffer from a loss of information.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}I have focused on this approach that does not suffer from information loss, where I simply repeat values the appropriate number of times to 'fill in the data holes'.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}So here there are only three trait values (represented by the different colours) that are appropriately repeated.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Similarly the environmental variables are also repeated appropriately but abundance there is no repetition.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Obviously there is redundancy here but no loss of information.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Now there's no unique way to fill in the data holes by repetition, and so we need to provide some structure in order to do this appropriately.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}This structure comes from a classification of the table dimensions as representing  either replicates or groups of variables.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}I recommend applying these rules when deciding on such a classification, but as always with rules common sense should be applied as well.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}(READ SLIDE)\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}So abundance, environemental variables and traits are variables because we can discover no more of these by sampling more.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Of course after sampling more we may gain some insight that leads us collect more variables, but we are not discovering them directly through sampling.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}In contrast, sites and taxa are dimensions of replication because as we sample more we discover new sites and new taxa.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Therefore, we put the sites and taxa on the rows (where the replicates go) and abundance, environment and traits on the columns (where the variables go).\
