{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Legendre et al took a largely correlative approach to this fourth corner problem.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Here we take a more predictive approach based on regression analysis, so that this 0.8 is an estimate of the  effect of the interaction between the environmental variable and the trait on the community.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Within this predictive approach it makes sense to include a column and row of all ones that allows us to measure main effects and intercept terms, as well as interaction terms, as we'll see soon.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}To understand more clearly what this fourth corner means, I'm going to explain how these data might be analyzed from a more traditional predictive modeling framework.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}A common approach is to fit separate regression lines to each species and then see if there are any relationships between the estimated slopes and the traits.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Here we have the environmental variable on the x axis and abundance on the y axis.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}We see that species with the trait value in grey have a negative slope and those with the black trait value have a positive slope, suggesting an interaction between the trait and the environment.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}But this 2-step procedure takes eight parameters (a slope and intercept for each species) and no formal estimate of the effect of the trait.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Can we do better?  The answer is yes.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}In this figure I've put the data for all of the species on a single graph and fit a single model to all of these data simultaneously.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}This table is the fourth corner, and contains the coefficient estimates of this model,\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}The 1.15 is the overall intercept, which gives the mean abundance of any species regardless of their trait value when the environmental variable is at zero.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}The 0.46 gives the main effect of the trait, which is positive because the black line for trait value positive one is greater than the grey line for trait value negative one, when the environmental variable is at zero.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}The negative 0.15 is the main effect of the environment, which is the slope that would be obtained without regard to the trait value.  There is not much of a relationship here.,\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}But there is a strong interaction between the environment and the trait, as the black species have a positive relationship with the environmental variable whereas the grey species have the opposite trend.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Now this model has only four parameters (instead of eight) and we have formal estimates of the effect of the trait.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}This model would be known in the statistics literature as a bilinear model.\
