\pard\tx940\tx1440\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1440\fi-1440\ql\qnatural\pardirnatural
\ls3\ilvl1\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}My focus in this talk will be on statistical methods for understanding how traits influence community structure.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}An important recent research focus in this area has been on how phylogenies can be used as a surrogate for functional traits.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}The idea here is that closely related species might often display similar functional traits, as a result of their shared evolutionary history.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Here is a cartoon example where more closely related species have more similar leaf colour.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}So, because functional traits can be difficult to measure, it might be possible to use existing phylogenetic knowledge to detect the effects of traits on community structure.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}There has been much recent methodological work on how to statistically test such hypotheses.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Here is an example from a recent issue of Ecology Letters.  Don't bother looking closely here.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}But there is surprisingly much less work on using phylogenetic and trait data to make predictive models of community structure, but this work here by Ives and Godfrey on ?? foodwebs is a rare expection.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Yet, as Rob Peters taught us, the ability to make accurate predictions often represents more useful scientific progress then reports of hypothesis tests alone.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Here we present a simple yet general approach to developing predictive models of community structure that use species characteristics as predictors.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li720\fi-720\ql\qnatural\pardirnatural
\ls3\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	
\f1 \uc0\u9642 
\f0 	}ILLUSTRATIVE EXAMPLE\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1440\fi-1440\ql\qnatural\pardirnatural
\ls3\ilvl1\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}We develop our techniques within the framework of the fourth corner problem, invented by Legendre et al 1997.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	} To explain this framework I use a simple fictitious data set with rows representing sites, columns representing species and the numbers are measures of abundance.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}A classical approach is to characterize the sites by environmental variables, like this one, and then analyze the relationship between the community data and the environmental data.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Here we not only characterize the sites with environmental variables but also characterize the species with functional traits, like this.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Here we have a categorical trait like the presence or absence of a big spiny tail.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}So now we have three sets of measured observed data: the trait data, the community data and the environment data.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}But there is this fourth corner down here, where this 0.8 is.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}This 0.8 is a statistic that characterizes the relationship between the three data tables.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Legendre et al took a largely correlative approach to this fourth corner problem.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Here we take a more predictive approach based on regression analysis, so that this 0.8 is an estimate of the  effect of the interaction between the environmental variable and the trait on the community.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Within this predictive approach it makes sense to include a column and row of all ones that allows us to measure main effects and intercept terms, as well as interaction terms, as we'll see soon.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}To understand more clearly what this fourth corner means, I'm going to explain how these data might be analyzed from a more traditional predictive modeling framework.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}A common approach is to fit separate regression lines to each species and then see if there are any relationships between the estimated slopes and the traits.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Here we have the environmental variable on the x axis and abundance on the y axis.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}We see that species with the trait value in grey have a negative slope and those with the black trait value have a positive slope, suggesting an interaction between the trait and the environment.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}But this 2-step procedure takes eight parameters (a slope and intercept for each species) and no formal estimate of the effect of the trait.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Can we do better?  The answer is yes.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}In this figure I've put the data for all of the species on a single graph and fit a single model to all of these data simultaneously.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}This table is the fourth corner, and contains the coefficient estimates of this model,\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}The 1.15 is the overall intercept, which gives the mean abundance of any species regardless of their trait value when the environmental variable is at zero.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}The 0.46 gives the main effect of the trait, which is positive because the black line for trait value positive one is greater than the grey line for trait value negative one, when the environmental variable is at zero.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}The negative 0.15 is the main effect of the environment, which is the slope that would be obtained without regard to the trait value.  There is not much of a relationship here.,\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}But there is a strong interaction between the environment and the trait, as the black species have a positive relationship with the environmental variable whereas the grey species have the opposite trend.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Now this model has only four parameters (instead of eight) and we have formal estimates of the effect of the trait.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}This model would be known in the statistics literature as a bilinear model.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li720\fi-720\ql\qnatural\pardirnatural
\ls3\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	
\f1 \uc0\u9642 
\f0 	}BILINEAR SOLUTION TO THE FORTH CORNER PROBLEM\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1440\fi-1440\ql\qnatural\pardirnatural
\ls3\ilvl1\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}And we are proposing that bilinear modeling can provide a predictively relevant solution to the fourth corner problem.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}This data table can be represented more abstractly like this.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Where we have any matrix Z of traits or phylogenetic information, matrix Y of community data and matrix X of environmental data.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}We will always have a fourth corner down here, C, with this set up.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}OK so to describe the bilinear model I'm going to have to get into a little math.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}I'm always going to use y's for community data, x's for environmental data and z's for trait data.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}And i to index sites, j for species, k for environmental variables and l for traits.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}The classical multivariate linear model (sometimes called redundancy analysis), models the abundance of the jth species at the ith site as a linear function of the environmental data plus some error.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}The bilinear model, on the other hand, modifies this classical model by incorporating traits.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Now the abundances are modeled as a linear function of the interactions between traits and environmental variables plus some error.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}There is an important difference between the coefficients of these two models.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}The b's are like regression slopes and since they have a j subscript, it means that each species gets their own set of parameters.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}This is the first model I used when analyzing the fictitious data, where each species was fitted separately.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}In contrast, the bilinear model coefficients, c, have no j subscript therefore the model is fitted to all species simultaneously in one step.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}These c coefficients form the fourth corner and are the estimated interaction effects between traits and environmental variables.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}What does this all mean?\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}For one thing, bilinear models have better statistical power then classical multivariate linear models.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}This is essentially because the species act as replicates for making inferences about the effect of traits, just as the sites act as replicates for making inferences about the effect of the environment.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}On the other hand, classical multivariate linear models only use sites as replicates.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}So the multivariate nature of community data is no longer a challenge to overcome...it is an advantage.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Each new species that we sample is a replicate that provides new information about the effect of traits on community composition.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}There are no bilinear parameters to represent each species, only parameters to represent traits.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Therefore, bilinear models are more parcimonious than multivariate linear models whenever there are fewer traits than species.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Well, there's no such thing as a free lunch, so what is the price to pay for this increased parsimony and power?\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Well, bilinear models are more difficult to specify because we not only need to decide which environmental variables to measure but also which traits to measure.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Next I'll show an example of how this apparent difficulty can actually lead to insight about our study systems.\
