\ls3\ilvl1\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}I analyzed the urban bird community data of Dol\'e9dec et al 1996.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}These data consist of 51 sites, 40 species, 11 environmental variables and 4 species traits.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}We modeled the community as presence-absences, therefore, we used this logistic version of the bilinear model.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Any logistic regression software can be 'tricked' into fitting this model.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Here is a graphical representation of the resulting fourth corner.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}The rows are the environmental variables and the columns are the traits.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}The colours give the standardized coefficients.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Standardized coefficients have the nice property that coefficients greater than 1.96 and less then -1.96 can be interpreted as approximately significant at the 0.05 level.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}Here we have very few significant interactions except that scrub breeders tend to prefer more vegetation cover, quieter sites without nearby coniferous vegetation or farm land.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}There are also strong negative intercept terms for all functional groups indicating low levels of occurence overall.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}So we can do standard hypothesis testing with the bilinear model.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}But we can also go beyond hypothesis testing and make predictions.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}The next step to predictive modeling is to see how well the predictions fit the data that were used to estimate the parameters.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}The colours here represent the fitted probabilities of occurrence of species here and sites here.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8259 	}The largely blue colour of this graph indicates low levels of occurrence overall.\
